p.me:
\begin{split}
(a*b)*(a*b) &=a*(b*(a*b))\quad \textrm{   Why?} \\
		&=a* ((b*a)*b)\quad \textrm{   Why?}\\
		&= a*((a*b)*b)\quad \textrm{   Why?}\\
		&= a*(a*(b*b))\quad \textrm{   Why?}\\ 
		&= (a*a)*(b*b)\quad \textrm{   Why?}
\end{split}

example.p:
 Consider the set of \(2\times 2\) real matrices, \(M_{2\times 2}(\mathbb{R})\), with the operation of matrix multiplication.
In this context,  can be interpreted as saying that if \(A B = B A\),  then \((A B)^2= A^2B^2\).  One pair of matrices that this
theorem applies to is \(\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 2 & 1 \\
 1 & 2 \\
\end{array}
\right)\) and \(\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 3 & -4 \\
 -4 & 3 \\
\end{array}
\right)\).
